<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="211" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[159,772,1003,1300]" box="[159,345,1003,1029]" pageId="19" pageNumber="211">
<emphasis box="[159,345,1003,1029]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="211">Taxonomic note</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[159,772,1003,1300]" pageId="19" pageNumber="211">
DNA barcodes suggest several genetically distinct clusters within bats currently referred to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Francis et al., 2010)" baseAuthorityName="Francis" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[159,535,1104,1130]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="thomasi">
<emphasis box="[159,283,1104,1130]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="211">R. thomasi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Francis" box="[297,527,1104,1130]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Francis" pageId="19" pageNumber="211" pagination="12575" refId="ref30303" refString="FRANCIS, C. M., A. V. BORISENKO, N. V. IVANOVA, J. L. EGER, B. K. LIM, A. GUILLEN- SERVENT, S. V. KRUSKOP, I. MACKIE, and P. D. N. HEBERT. 2010. The role of DNA barcodes in understanding and conservation of mammal diversity in Southeast Asia. PLoS ONE, 5: e 12575. doi: 10.1371 / journal. pone. 0012575." type="journal article" year="2010">
Francis 
<emphasis box="[392,442,1104,1130]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="211">et al</emphasis>
., 2010
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Some of these have been labelled as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1835" box="[373,481,1138,1164]" class="Mammalia" family="Rhinolophidae" genus="Rhinolophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="211" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rouxii">
<emphasis box="[373,481,1138,1164]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="211">R. rouxii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but further taxonomic study comparing morphology, echolocation calls and genetics is needed to determine whether any of these represent distinct species and, if so, what are the appropriate names.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
